=== TASK ===
# User Profile & Child Management

## Overview
Build a robust User Profile system where a parent can manage their account details and create, view, update, and delete multiple child profiles. Each child profile includes age, grade, and learning preferences. The feature must support authentication/authorization, data integrity, audit trails for profile changes, export (CSV/JSON) and deletion workflows to address privacy requests, and seamless integration with existing pages and the StudySpark platform.

## Components to Build
- UserProfile Service
  - Model: User (id, name, email, contactInfo, etc.)
  - Relationships: One-to-many with ChildProfile
  - Audit Trail: Change logs capturing who changed what when
  - Validation: Email format, required fields, password rules (if applicable)
- ChildProfile Service
  - Model: ChildProfile (id, userId, name, age, grade, learningPreferences)
  - Validation: Age range (e.g., 4–18), grade enums (K, 1–12, etc.), learningPreferences enum
  - Options: Multiple learning preferences per child (array)
  - Data export: CSV/JSON export per user or per child
- Authentication & Authorization
  - JWT/OAuth integration with permission checks (parent users only access their own profiles)
- API Layer
  - CRUD endpoints for User and Child profiles
  - Audit endpoints for retrieving change history
  - Export endpoints (CSV/JSON) with proper streaming/large-data handling
  - Privacy/deletion endpoints to comply with data deletion requests
- Database Layer
  - Relational schema with foreign key constraints
  - Indexes to optimize lookups by userId, childId
  - Soft delete support if required (e.g., isDeleted flag)
- Frontend UI Components & Pages
  - Profile Dashboard (page_p005)
  - Child Management Page (page_p012)
  - Profile Settings & Child List Page (page_p002)
  - Forms for creating/updating parent profile and child profiles
  - Validation feedback, inline hints, and accessible error messages
  - Audit trail UI for profile changes
- Localization & Accessibility
  - ARIA roles, keyboard navigation, and screen reader-friendly labels

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack alignment: React (or your existing framework), TypeScript, state management as appropriate.
- State and data handling
  - Use useState with proper default shapes: e.g., useState<UserProfile[]>([]) for arrays, and useState<ChildProfile[]>([]) for child lists.
  - Guard all array operations with (data ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : [] to avoid runtime crashes.
  - When consuming API responses, validate shapes: const users = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- Components to Build
  - ProfileHeaderCard: Displays parent name, email, quick edit actions, and an audit summary snippet.
  - ChildCard: Displays a child’s name, age, grade, and a summary of learning preferences (with pill badges).
  - ChildManagementPanel: List of ChildCard components with add/edit/delete actions, multi-select for batch operations.
  - UserProfileForm: Create/edit parent profile with fields (name, email, phone, address). Include password field if relevant.
  - ChildProfileForm: Create/edit child profile with fields (name, age, grade, learningPreferences). Support multi-select for learningPreferences (e.g., ["Playful","Exam-like","Research-based","Printable","Interactive in-app"]).
  - AuditTrailPanel: Read-only view or compact timeline for changes to user/child profiles.
  - ExportButton: Triggers CSV/JSON export for current user’s data (with options to export all children or specific child data).
  - PrivacyDeleteModal: Confirm data deletion; trigger backend deletion endpoint; show progress/status.
- Validation Rules (Frontend)
  - Age: integer between 4 and 18
  - Grade: one of predefined enum values (e.g., K, 1–12, or custom mapping)
  - Learning Preferences: at least one selection; disallow invalid values
  - Email format validation; required fields enforcement
  - Auditable fields: capture lastModified, modifiedBy on edits
- API Integration
  - Use a consistent API client layer; handle loading and error states gracefully
  - Debounce or batch updates where appropriate to avoid excessive calls
  - Ensure null-safe access to response data (e.g., const items = response?.data ?? [])
- UX considerations
  - Cards with hover/active states, rounded corners (20–28px), soft shadows
  - Pill-shaped badges for learning preferences
  - Clear CTA hierarchy: primary actions (Save, Add) prominent; secondary actions subdued
  - Consistent bottom/top navigation integration as per project style
- Data Export
  - Implement CSV export with header mapping: user fields + array-of-children flattened
  - Implement JSON export with a clean structure: { user: {...}, children: [{...}, ...] }
  - Respect privacy controls (omit sensitive fields as needed)

